Method : A method is a block of code where we write the business logic of an application.

Types of Methods
Instance Method
Static Method

1. Instance Method
Definition: An instance method belongs to an object of a class.

Key Points:
Accessed using object reference.
Memory is allocated when the object is created.
Can directly access instance variables.
Can access static members directly.

Example:
class Demo {
    int a = 10;

    void show() {
        System.out.println(a);
    }
}

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo d = new Demo();
        d.show();
    }
}

2. Static Method
Definition: A static method belongs to the class, not to any object.

Key Points:
Accessed using class name.
Memory is allocated during class loading.
Can directly access only static variables.
Cannot directly access instance variables.

Example:
class Demo {
    static int b = 20;

    static void display() {
        System.out.println(b);
    }
}

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo.display();
    }
}

Difference Between Instance and Static Method
Instance Method										Static Method
Access using object								Access using class name
Memory at object creation						Memory at class loading
Can access instance variables					Cannot access instance variables directly
Object required									Object not required


Method Syntax : 
==============
modifier returnType methodName(parameters) throws Exception {
    // method body
}

Modifier list  : public, private, protected, static, final, abstract
Return type : void â†’ returns nothing, int, String, double, boolean
Method name : m1(int a), m2 (string b)
Method Signature = Method Name + Parameter List
